Which California National Park has the highest average rating of its âeasyâ trails?

easy_trails_criteria = (ca_trails['elevation_gain'] < 500) & (ca_trails['length'] < 5000) & (ca_trails['difficulty_rating'] < 4) #easy trails

2.1 recommended trails function


def rec_trails(dataset, park_name, min_elev=0, max_elev=float('inf'), min_rating=0, trail_type=None):
    trails = dataset[dataset['area_name'] == park_name] #filter park
    trails = trails[trails['elevation_gain'] >= min_elev] #min elevation
    trails = trails[trails['elevation_gain'] <= max_elev] #max elevation
    trails = trails[trails['avg_rating'] >= min_rating] # avg trail rating

    if trail_type is not None: #filter trail if specified
        trails = trails[trails['route_type'] == trail_type]

    return trails

    return park_name

2.2 scrape_temps function

def scrape_temps(month=None):

    base_url = "https://www.extremeweatherwatch.com/us-state-averages"

    if month:
        m_url = f"{base_url}/month-{month.lower()}"  #modifying url to get the correct selection based on the selected month
    else:
        m_url = base_url

    response = requests.get(m_url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser') #http request
    table = soup.find_all("table",
                  attrs={
                      "class": "bordered-table sort-table"
                  }
                  )[0]

    data = []
    for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
      cells = row.find_all('td')
      if len(cells) > 0:
        city = cells[0].get_text(strip=True)
        high = cells[1].get_text(strip=True)
        low = cells[2].get_text(strip=True)
        prec = cells[3].get_text(strip=True).split()[0]
        data.append([city, high, low, prec])
    df = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['City', 'Highest Temp', 'Lowest Temp', 'Precipitation'])
    df
    return df
